flowchart LR

  subgraph INTENT["1. Path objective"]
    G1["Turn already joined runtime context into online feature state that the live decision path can actually use"]
    G2["Keep this path narrower than decisioning, guardrail posture, or audit truth"]
    G3["Answer whether the platform now has usable feature truth for this event with honest readiness and freshness semantics"]
  end

  subgraph ENTRY["2. Entry basis"]
    E1["The entry is not raw source data and not traffic alone"]
    E2["The entry is the event and context state already bound by the earlier RTDL paths: admitted behavioural traffic, joined context, and current entity and relationship state"]
    E3["Traffic stays thin and context is joined inside the platform"]
    E4["The runtime semantic world is pinned tightly: behavioural_streams are the traffic side; arrival_events_5B, s1_arrival_entities_6B, and flow-anchor outputs are context and join surfaces; s4_* truth products are not live runtime inputs"]
    E5["The active required output scope is exactly four oracle outputs: s3_event_stream_with_fraud_6B, arrival_events_5B, s1_arrival_entities_6B, s3_flow_anchor_with_fraud_6B"]
  end

  subgraph SPINE["5. Broad route logic"]
    R1["Joined runtime context + current entity and relationship state"]
    R2["Online feature materialization and serve surface"]
    R3["Feature-ready truth for the live decision path"]
    R4["Downstream decisioning can consume explicit feature state"]
    R5["Feature boundary is owned rather than implied"]
  end

  subgraph CARRIES["4. What the path carries"]
    C1["Lookup keys"]
    C2["Current projection state"]
    C3["Feature-group request semantics"]
    C4["Freshness and readiness posture that downstream decisioning will rely on"]
    C5["Graph-version shape contract"]
    C6["Feature-request key shape contract"]
    C7["Live diagnosis showed disagreement when graph-version came back in a shape downstream resolution did not accept"]
    C8["Another diagnosis narrowed warning noise to redundant event_id:* requests when the projector already keyed traffic by flow_id first"]
    C9["This boundary carries explicit contracts, not just data blobs"]
  end

  subgraph LOGIC["6. Logical design reading"]
    L1["The platform treats feature truth as different from context truth"]
    L2["The system is not saying once context exists, the decision can use it"]
    L3["There is a separate boundary where context becomes feature-ready state"]
    L4["That boundary must be honest about availability, freshness, and missingness"]
    L5["That is why the online feature section treats required feature-group availability, freshness truth, and false missing-feature posture as distinct concerns"]
  end

  subgraph SEATING["7. Concrete seating in the current wired system"]
    S1["The path is seated across the runtime bus topics feeding RTDL"]
    S2["The RTDL namespace and worker surfaces host the online feature surface"]
    S3["Joined context is projected onward from the context boundary into the online feature and entity surfaces"]
    S4["Online feature state is written into Aurora"]
    S5["There is a handle-based read seam to Redis"]
    S6["Managed stream-processing surfaces for RTDL feature materialization remain retained rather than the primary reader-facing active output path in this notebook's copied baseline wired view"]
    S7["This path is visible as distinct feature-serving and readiness surface with live counters such as applied events, missing-feature signals, snapshot failures, and checkpoint age"]
  end

  subgraph RATIONALE["8. Why the design looks like this"]
    Y1["The platform deliberately chose to make feature state explicit rather than leaving it implicit inside downstream code"]
    Y2["It also pins feature engineering to observed data behavior rather than schema-only assumptions"]
    Y3["When feature defects appeared, they were handled as explicit contract seams: graph-version payload shape, requester/projector key-shape alignment, and missing-key telemetry"]
    Y4["Those defects were not hidden behind vague feature-red language"]
    Y5["This is the opposite of accidental design"]
  end

  subgraph CONTRACT["9. What larger contracts are shaping this path"]
    X1["The data-engine contract keeps traffic thin and forces the platform to join context internally rather than smuggling truth into the payload"]
    X2["The runtime and learning separation contract forbids truth-product leakage and future-only fields from live runtime surfaces"]
    X3["The runtime path is explicitly past and present only, and s4_* truth products are learning-only"]
    X4["The RTDL component law says the online feature plane must be semantically correct, time-correct, replay-safe, and observable"]
    X5["Freshness, checkpoint age, restart behavior, and missing-feature truth are all part of the boundary, not optional diagnostics"]
  end

  subgraph TRADEOFFS["10. Trade-offs and constraints"]
    T1["This path deliberately adds one more explicit boundary to the RTDL graph"]
    T2["That costs more state, more health and readiness surface, and more requester/projector contract edges"]
    T3["But it buys the ability to distinguish context exists from features are truly usable"]
    T4["It also lets the system tell whether a red posture comes from actual missing feature state, freshness issues, or contract-shape mismatch like graph-version or redundant-key seams"]
    T5["That is the trade-off: more boundary discipline in exchange for less semantic ambiguity"]
  end

  subgraph NECESSITY["11. Necessity test"]
    N1["If this path is removed, the platform can still ingest traffic, still build joined context, and still draw boxes called decision guardrail and decision formation"]
    N2["But it loses clean answers to whether the required features are actually present and fresh enough"]
    N3["It also loses a clean answer to whether missing is real or just partial key coverage"]
    N4["It becomes unclear whether decisioning is failing because inputs are insufficient or because the online feature plane never made feature state usable"]
    N5["Without this path, decisioning would sit on top of an unowned feature boundary"]
    N6["That would weaken A immediately because the system would have context and decisions but no explicit owner for the thing that connects them"]
  end

  subgraph CLOSURE["3. Owned outcome and 12. What this path proves for A"]
    O1["The platform can now say which feature groups are available for this event"]
    O2["Freshness and readiness are real and explicit"]
    O3["Missing features are distinguishable from key-shape or partial-coverage artifacts"]
    O4["Owned outcome: feature-ready runtime truth"]
    A1["Purpose claim:<br/>the platform has a distinct job for turning context into usable feature state"]
    A2["Intentionality claim:<br/>the online feature plane is a named, contract-governed boundary rather than an accident of downstream code"]
    A3["Materialization claim:<br/>the path is concretely seated in the runtime bus, the RTDL namespace and online feature surface, the bounded four-surface runtime oracle set, the shared state stores, and the live feature-readiness counters"]
    A4["Contract claim:<br/>the path is governed by thin-traffic semantics, no-future and runtime-truth separation, and explicit requester/projector compatibility"]
    A5["Constraint-awareness claim:<br/>the design already knows this boundary can fail semantically even when the rest of RTDL looks alive, which is why missing-feature truth and key-shape and graph-version seams are surfaced rather than hidden"]
    A6["Material participation signal:<br/>the online feature surface is visibly processing current-run events and exposing missing-feature, snapshot-failure, and checkpoint-age signals as first-class surfaces"]
    A7["A-level meaning:<br/>joined runtime context becomes explicitly usable feature truth instead of leaving decisioning to infer whether inputs are really ready"]
  end

